/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom sexualized selfies and hidden camera documentaries to the bouncers monitoring patrons at Australian nightclubs, the ubiquity of contemporary surveillance goes far beyond the National Security Agency’s bulk data collection or the proliferation of security cameras on every corner.Expanding the Gaze is a collection of important new empirical and theoretical works that demonstrate the significance of the gendered dynamics of surveillance. Bringing together contributors from criminology, sociology, communication studies, and women’s studies, the eleven essays in the volume suggest that we cannot properly understand the implications of the rapid expansion of surveillance practices today without paying close attention to its gendered nature. Together, they constitute a timely interdisciplinary contribution to the development of feminist surveillance studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aElectronic surveillancexPolitical aspects. 0aElectronic surveillancexSex differences. 0aElectronic surveillancexSocial aspects. 0aFeminism. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aBailey, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruckert, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Mia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitz-Gibbon, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrench, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, Marilou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuta, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeynen, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeynen, Robert, eeditor.4edt4h